{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"X3\n    \n      On-call pressure simulator · crisis design drill\n      Random 1-in-week: app pages you at weird hour with a \"PAGER ALERT\". Production is down. 5-minute crisis design challenge — you must pick a pattern + explain fix + explain tradeoffs. Pressure simulation. The closest you'll get to SRE real-world stress without actual outages.\n      \n        🚨\n        PAGER · P1 INCIDENT\n        Database connection pool is exhausted. Checkout failing. 5k users affected. What pattern do you reach for?\n        \n          ⏱ 4:52\n          Answer →","choice":"x3","id":null,"timestamp":1776686362464}
{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"X5\n    \n      Design mysteries · whodunit, but for software\n      A fictional e-commerce company's system is broken. You're handed: 3 class diagrams, 5 commits, 2 angry customer reviews, 1 incident post-mortem. Find the root cause. Whodunit style. \"Was it Observer's missing unsubscribe? Singleton's thread race? Factory's bad constructor?\" Each mystery = a pattern masterclass in context.\n      \n        🔍 THE CASE OF THE 3AM PAGER\n        \n          \"Checkout was working fine at 2:50 AM. By 3:15 AM, 40% of requests were failing. No deploys happened. No traffic spike. Nobody touched the database. The only change: someone rolled out a new Observer for analytics at 2:55...\"\n        \n        \n          📋 Evidence\n          👥 Witnesses\n          🧑‍💻 Suspects","choice":"x5","id":null,"timestamp":1776686381978}
{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"X7\n    \n      Failure portfolio · celebrate your wrong answers\n      Inverse achievements. Your failures become a public portfolio (opt-in) showing the bold mistakes you tried. \"Attempted Visitor pattern on a graph with 200 nodes · learned why double-dispatch is painful\". Normalizes failure as essential to learning. Shows growth, not perfection.\n      \n        🏅 My Failure Portfolio · 14 proud mistakes\n        \n          \n            Tried Visitor on 200-node graph · \"why double-dispatch hurts at scale\"\n          \n          \n            Singleton for session state · \"global state in disguise, learned the hard way\"\n          \n          \n            5-level inheritance hierarchy · \"not everything needs a base class\"","choice":"x7","id":null,"timestamp":1776686406236}
{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"X9\n    \n      Physical product · card deck + poster pack shipped\n      Thing that sits on engineers' desks. 36-pattern playing-card deck (actual shippable). Pattern poster set (6 large format, blueprint style). Notebook with pattern reference in back. Sold via Shopify. Architex-branded merch with actual pedagogical value.\n      \n        \n          \n            \n              🃏\n              36-Card Deck\n              $25\n            \n          \n          \n            \n              🖼\n              6-Poster Pack\n              $40\n            \n          \n          \n            \n              📔\n              Pattern Journal\n              $18\n            \n          \n        \n      \n      Print-on-demand via Shopify. Passive side revenue. Brand signal.","choice":"x9","id":null,"timestamp":1776686413109}
{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"X10\n    \n      Job application assistant · company-specific interview prep\n      User tells app: \"Interviewing at Stripe in 2 weeks\". System creates targeted plan: \"Stripe asks Payment System 40% of the time. Let's drill: Parking Lot, Vending Machine, Money Transfer. Their eval rubric emphasizes idempotency — you're weak there, here are 3 lessons.\" Adaptive, specific, just-in-time.\n      \n        \n          S\n          \n            Stripe · Senior Backend\n            Interview in 14 days · 2-week sprint plan ready\n          \n        \n        \n          Day 1-3: Payment domain patterns (5 drills) · your weak area\n          Day 4-7: Idempotency lessons · Learn + custom problem\n          Day 8-11: Stripe-style mock interviews (hostile mode)\n          Day 12-14: Review + calm · no new patterns","choice":"x10","id":null,"timestamp":1776686415570}
{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"X11\n    \n      Community Hall of Fame · \"best solutions ever submitted\"\n      Curated leaderboard: \"Most elegant Parking Lot ever (upvoted 2.3k times). Most minimal Chat Room (847). Most controversial Vending Machine\". Each entry shows author, their reasoning, what made it special. Inspires by showing creative excellence.\n      \n        🏆 HALL OF FAME\n        \n          \n            🥇\n            \n              Most Elegant Parking Lot\n              @anshul-garg27 · 6 classes · 2.3k upvotes\n            \n            View →\n          \n          \n            🥈\n            \n              Most Minimal Chat Room\n              @maya_l · 4 classes · 847 upvotes\n            \n          \n          \n            🥉\n            \n              Most Controversial Vending Machine\n              @kenji_v · functional approach · 652","choice":"x11","id":null,"timestamp":1776686498687}
{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"X12\n    \n      Time capsule · letter to your future self\n      After completing your first 5 patterns: \"Write a short letter to yourself 1 year from now. What do you hope you've learned? What do you hope you'll remember?\" Sealed. Delivered exactly 1 year later. Emotionally anchors learning to identity, not just content.\n      \n        ── TO OPEN · APRIL 2027 ──\n        \n          Dear future me,\n          I'm writing this after finishing my first 5 patterns. Right now, Factory Method still feels clever and fresh. I hope by the time you read this, it feels obvious — because if it does, that means you've grown.\n          Also: please don't be tempted to Singleton-everything. I know it's tempting...\n        \n        A. G.","choice":"x12","id":null,"timestamp":1776686502978}
